\begin_layout Standard
Esta ultima ecuacion esta relacionada con dos problemas matematicos Booleanos
 de interes en la criptografia: el balanceo de una funcion booleana y el
 problema de biseccion de los coeficientes binomiales (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cusick2,cusick2.1,mitchell"

\end_inset

).
 A solution 
\begin_inset Formula $(\delta_{0},\delta_{1},\cdots,\delta_{n})$
\end_inset

 to the equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{j=0}^{n}\delta_{j}\binom{n}{j}=0,\,\,\,\delta_{j}\in\{-1,1\},\label{bisec}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is said to give a bisection of the binomial coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq j\leq n.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To finish this introduction the formula closed for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mathbb{F}_{q}}(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,k})$
\end_inset

 is not only to computational improvement over the formal definition of
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mathbb{F}_{q}}(F)$
\end_inset

, but also provide a link to a similar problem to the problem of bisecting
 binomial coefficients for multinomial coefficients.
 For example.
 suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}=\mathbb{Z}_{3}$
\end_inset

 is the Galois field of 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 elements.
 Then a explicit formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mathbb{F}_{3}}(\boldsymbol{e}_{4,2})$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{\mathbb{F}_{3}}(\boldsymbol{e}_{4,2})=\sum_{m_{1}=0}^{4}\sum_{m_{2}=0}^{4-m_{1}}{4 \choose m_{0}^{*},m_{1},m_{2}}e^{\left(\frac{2\pi i}{3}\right)\left(\Lambda_{1,-1}(2,m_{1},m_{2})\right)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{1,-1}(2,m_{1},m_{2})=\sum_{j=0}^{m_{2}}{\text{m_{2}} \choose j}{\text{m_{1}} \choose 2-j}\left(-1\right)^{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}^{*}=4-(m_{1}+m_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the fact that exponential sums of symmetric polynomials over
 finite fields can be expressed as multinomial sums is later used in the
 proof of closed formulas for them.
 The proof of the closed formulas also depends on a classical result in
 number theory known as Lucas' Theorem.
 
\end_layout

